Compressing color spaces¶

A typical true color image has 24-bit depth, but in most images many of those will not be used. We can use k-means to reduce the color palette, thinking of the cluster centers as the reduced color palette.

In [7]:
# we use plot_pixels to visualize
def plot_pixels(data, title, colors=None, N=10000):
    if colors is None:
        colors = data
    # if N is specified, we choose N radom data points
    rng = np.random.RandomState(0)
    i = rng.permutation(data.shape[0])[:N]
    colors = colors[i]
    # we produce 2 plots that visualize a subspace of 3d
    # point cloud: Red vs Green and Red vs Blue
    pixel = data[i].T
    R, G, B = pixel[0], pixel[1], pixel[2]
    # first plot
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(16,6))
    ax[0].scatter(R, G, color=colors, marker='.')
    ax[0].set(xlabel='Red', ylabel='Green', xlim=(0,1),\
             ylim=(0,1))
    # second plot
    ax[1].scatter(R, B, color=colors, marker='.')
    ax[1].set(xlabel='Red', ylabel='Blue', xlim=(0,1),\
             ylim=(0,1))
    fig.suptitle(title, size=20)
In [8]:
# Let's try it
plot_pixels(img_data, title='Input color space: 16 million '\
           'possible colors')
In [9]:
# Reduce the 16 million colors to only 16
criteria = (cv2.TERM_CRITERIA_EPS + \
           cv2.TERM_CRITERIA_MAX_ITER, 10, 1.0)
flags = cv2.KMEANS_RANDOM_CENTERS
img_data = img_data.astype(np.float32)
compactness, labels, centers = cv2.kmeans(\
    img_data, 16, None, criteria, 10, flags)

These 16 colors correspond to the 16 cluster labels contained in the labels vector. So we want all data points with label 0 to be colored according to row 0 in the centers array; all data points with label 1 to be colored according to row 1 in the centers array; and so on. In other words, we want to use labels as an index into the centers array--these are our new colors

In [11]:
new_colors = centers[labels].reshape((-1, 3))
In [12]:
# re-plot data
plot_pixels(img_data, colors=new_colors,\
           title="Reduce color space: 16 colors")
